What has been said above will serve to explain the necessity of here supplementing the narrative os Tacitus by such a geographical and chronological sketch as will make it intelligible.

It may be sufficient for the former purpose to trace the three chief mountain systems forming the highlands of Armenia and the river basius and plains of various elevation enclosed by them.¹ The central and highest range, that of the Dujik mountainS, a prolongation of the Anti- Taurus, parts at its western extremity the two branches of the Upper Euphrates, the Murad and the Jephrat or Rara-Su3 and is prolonged under the names of Dujik Dagh, Binghol Dagh, and others, rising at its eastern extremity to the two highest points in the whole country, those of Great and Little Ararat; at the soot os the latter of which the basin of the Erasch (Araxes) is j0ined to that of its tributary the Balyk. The southern range, treated as a prolongation of Taurus, or Taurus NiphateS, parts the basin of the Murad from that of the Upper Tigris⁸ under the name os Mush Dagh, and divides at the great plain of Lake Van into the Arjerosch and Erdoz Dagh south of the lake, and Jebel Nimrud and Sapan Dagh at the north os it, rising further to the north-east to the Ala Dagh,⁸ in which the Murad and Balyk find their source and water- shed. The northern range, enclosing the whole country in its sweep, divides in its western portion the basin of the Rara-Su from that of the Ioruk (Akampsis), and in its eastern that of the Araxes from that of the Kur (Cyrus); the watershed of the Kara-Su and Araxes being found on the high table-landS, the highest in the whole country and near 7000 feet
